'Cangjie programming language_function_overload_function_overloading_definition': 'In Cangjie code language, Function overloading in Cangjie allows multiple functions with the same name to be defined in the same scope, as long as their parameter lists differ. This can be achieved by varying the number of parameters or the types of parameters.'

Code_Example:
// Overloading by parameter count
func add(a: Int64, b: Int64): Int64 {
    return a + b
}
func add(a: Int64, b: Int64, c: Int64): Int64 {
    return a + b + c
}
println(add(1, 2)) // Output: 3
println(add(1, 2, 3)) // Output: 6

'Cangjie programming language_function_overload_function_overloading_generic': 'In Cangjie code language, Two generic functions with the same name can be overloaded if their non-generic parts differ after renaming the type parameters. If the non-generic parts are identical, it is considered a redefinition error.'

Code_Example:
interface I1{}
interface I2{}
func f1<X, Y>(a: X, b: Y) {}
func f1<Y, X>(a: X, b: Y) {} // Ok: after rename generic type parameter, it will be 'func f1<X, Y>(a: Y, b: X)'
func f2<T>(a: T) where T <: I1 {}
func f2<T>(a: T) where T <: I2 {} // Error, not overloading

'Cangjie programming language_function_overload_function_overloading_constructors': 'In Cangjie code language, Two constructor parameters within the same class are different, constituting an overload.'

Code_Example:
class C {
    var a: Int64
    var b: Float64
    public init(a: Int64, b: Float64) {
        this.a = a
        this.b = b
    }
    public init(a: Int64) {
        b = 0.0
        this.a = a
    }
}

'Cangjie programming language_function_overload_function_overloading_resolution': 'In Cangjie code language, When a function is called, the compiler resolves which function to call based on the following rules:
Prefer functions from higher scope levels (inner scopes have higher levels).
If multiple functions have the same highest scope level, choose the most specific function.
If no unique most specific function exists, the compiler reports an error.'

Code_Example:
open class Base {}
class Sub <: Base {}
func outer() {
    func g(a: Sub) {
        print("1")
    }
    func inner() {
        func g(a: Base) {
            print("2")
        }
        g(Sub())   // Output: 2
    }
}
